<DocsLayout title="Behavioral Round" section="Rounds" description="STAR method, leadership principles, and interpersonal skills assessment">
  <h2 id="overview">Overview</h2>
  <p>Behavioral interviews gauge soft skills, emotional intelligence, and leadership potential. Every company includes this component because no one wants to work with brilliant jerks.</p>

  <h2 id="question-types">Question Types</h2>
  <h3>Past Experience ("Tell me about a time...")</h3>
  <p>The interviewer expects a real example from your work history. Use the STAR method:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>S</strong>ituation Set the scene (company, project, role)</li>
    <li><strong>T</strong>ask What was the challenge?</li>
    <li><strong>A</strong>ction What did YOU specifically do?</li>
    <li><strong>R</strong>esult What was the measurable outcome?</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Hypotheticals ("How would you handle...")</h3>
  <p>No past example needed instead propose a solution. Always ask clarifying questions first!</p>
  <blockquote>
    "Would you like me to provide an example from my work history, or are you interested in how I would solve this problem if it arose?"
  </blockquote>

  <h2 id="preparation-matrix">Preparation Matrix</h2>
  <p>Build a table with themes as rows and projects as columns:</p>
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Theme</th><th>Project A</th><th>Project B</th><th>Project C</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><strong>Challenges</strong></td><td>Deployment mess → implemented CD</td><td>Low morale → created social events</td><td>Complex form logic → JSON schema</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Successes</strong></td><td>Reduced latency 1.5s → 750ms</td><td>Scaled 1K → 50K req/day</td><td>Beta launched with 1K users</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Failures</strong></td><td>Pushed bad date format to prod</td><td>—</td><td>Mismanaged partner relationship</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Leadership</strong></td><td>Presented vision to CTO</td><td>Led infra without being assigned</td><td>—</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Conflicts</strong></td><td>Senior engineers resisted change</td><td>—</td><td>Schema validation disagreement</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2 id="sample-questions">Sample Questions</h2>
  <h3>Past Experience</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Tell me about a time you had a conflict with a co-worker.</li>
    <li>Tell me about a time you needed to influence somebody else.</li>
    <li>Talk about a project you're most passionate about.</li>
    <li>Tell me about a time you met a tight deadline.</li>
    <li>What is the most constructive feedback you've received?</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Hypotheticals</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>How would you handle someone disengaged and not carrying their weight?</li>
    <li>What would you do if your manager wanted a technical approach you disagree with?</li>
    <li>A junior engineer is being excluded from team activities. How do you fix it?</li>
    <li>What would you do if you realized your team would miss a deadline?</li>
  </ol>

  <h2 id="tips">Pro Tips</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Quantify everything.</strong> Revenue, users, performance metrics, team velocity.</li>
    <li><strong>Show empathy.</strong> Never badmouth former employers or colleagues.</li>
    <li><strong>Talk about lessons learned.</strong> Companies want people who grow from mistakes.</li>
    <li><strong>Ask clarifying questions.</strong> Especially for hypotheticals clarify your relationship to the situation.</li>
  </ul>
</DocsLayout>
